    <p>
      Similar to Instablock you will also receive no Chip Damage and Knockback, but unlike
      Instablock you don't have to be in Neutral State to perform this move, which makes it a really
      good panic option. The only problem is if the incoming attack consists of more than one hit.
      In that case you will be locked into the animation and most likely get hit.
    </p>

    <SectionSubTitle title="Spiral Thrust" />
    <p>
      Spiral Thrust costs 1 Wirebug and let's the hunter perform two dashes into Any Direction. The
      startup of the first dash has a built in Guard Point that let's you block incoming Attacks. If
      you successfully block an Attacks your Lance will start glowing blue for 10 seconds giving you
      a 10% Raw Buff.
    </p>

    <p>
      The two dashes both have hitboxes that have 50MV and 80MV respectively. After the second dash
      you can follow up with a strong Finishing Attack that has a impressive 90MV. Most people don't
      know about this follow up and as you can see it's by far the strongest hit of the Combo. So
      make sure to not forget about it.
    </p>

    <p>
      In theory, if you manage to land all 3 hits on the monster's Weakspot, Spiral Thrust is one of
      the best Dps Moves Lance offers. In practice this turns out the surprisingly difficult though.
      Therefore many people prefer Anchor Rage with it's more consistent high Raw Buff.
    </p>

    <p>It's still a lot of fun to use so I would recommend trying it out for yourself.</p>

    <SectionSubTitle title="Skyward Thrust" />
    <p>
      Skyward Thrust is a very flashy looking move. It costs 1 Wirebug and let's you fly into the
      sky and perform a strong diving attack that can Pierce The Monster.
    </p>

    <p>
      The upwards move deals only 40MV. The downwards move on the other hand can Tick 1-3 Times
      depending on the monster's size. Each tick deals 80MV, so at max ticks that's an impressive
      240MV. When landing there's an additional small hit that deals 30MV.
    </p>

    <p>
      This makes Skyward Thrust the strongest move Lance has to offer. The problem is just that it
      doesn't work on all monsters. But on the monsters it does work on it's a lot of fun to use.
    </p>

    <p>
      Here's a list of some monsters that have easy skyward opening: Chameleos enrage + risen
      transform + body slam, Malzeno roar, Rathian flip, Narwa sac topple, Valstrax inhale + all
      wing slams, Bazelgeuse roar ...
    </p>

    <p>
      The list goes on and on. I personally just keep it equipped on my Secondary Scroll and just
      switch to it when I see an easy opening.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section title="Twin Vine Vs Sheathing Retreat">
    <p>
      Twin Vine and Sheathing Retreat are both very good moves that have their own advantages and
    </p>

    <SectionSubTitle title="Twin Vine" />
    <p>
      Twin Vine costs 1 Wirebug and let's you stab your kunai into the monster. On a hit you will be
      connected to the monster with a Silkbind Wire. You can then press the roll button to pull
      yourself towards the monster. Addiionally as long as the wire is connected you will receive
      Knockback reduction equal to the armor skill Guard Level 3.
    </p>

    <p>
      In my opinion this move is pretty bad. There's not really a reason to use it when there's many
      better gap closers like Dash Attack, Shield Charge, Guard Dash, Spiral Thrust or even
      Sheathing Retreat. The extra Knockback recution is nice but it's super conditional and the
      wire breaks easily so it's just better to slot more Guard in your set if you want more
      Knockback reduction.
    </p>

    <SectionSubTitle title="Sheathing Retreat" />
    <p>
      Sheathing Retreat costs 1 Wirebug as well and let's you sheathe your weapon immediately while
      also performing a jump backwards. Getting you out of Potentially Dangerous Situations.
    </p>

    <p>
      The move also has 40 iframes (@60 fps) on it's start up. Letting you evade Attacks that are
      difficult or impossible to block. For example if you time it with flaming Espinas stomp you
      can completely evade his nova, or you can evade rajang's lightning beam.
    </p>

    <p>
      It can also be used as a Gap Closer by turning around first, then sheathing retreating +
      buffering a mid air jump. Or you can use it to quickly access certain items mid air like flash
      Bombs. Overall it's a really good move that offers a lot of Utility and is definitely worth
      using.
    </p>
  </Section>
